83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
B-Engrossed
House Bill 4121
Ordered by the House March 4
Including House Amendments dated February 16 and March 4
Sponsored by Representatives EVANS, GOMBERG, JAVADI; Representatives ANDERSEN, CHAICHI, GAMBA,
NELSON, PHAM H, RIEKE SMITH (Presession filed.)
SUMMARY
The following summary is not prepared by the sponsors of the measure and is not a part of the body thereof subject
to consideration by the Legislative Assembly. It is an editor’s brief statement of the essential features of the
measure. The statement includes a measure digest written in compliance with applicable readability standards.
Digest: The Act creates new systems and structures and changes law to improve emergency
response in the state. (Flesch Readability Score: 65.1).
Creates [statewide emergency preparedness offices and authorities] authority to coordinate
emergency management. [Authorizes bonding for public safety projects.] Requires state agencies to
designate liaisons for emergency management.
Imposes duties on the Oregon Department of Emergency Management related to management
of emergency preparedness assets.
Modifies the definitions of and grant requirements for Resilience Hubs and Resilience Networks.
Authorizes certain training facilities to host overnight training activities. Requires the Oregon
Department of Emergency Management to obtain fingerprints of employees and contractors.
Authorizes counties to waive certain civil penalties related to food service facilities during
emergencies.
Requires the Department of the State Fire Marshal to study health coverage for firefighters.
[Requires legislative committees to identify a revenue source for certain public safety programs.]
Establishes grant programs for emergencies.
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT
2 Relating to emergency management; creating new provisions; and amending ORS 401.114, 401.913
3 and 409.760.
4 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
5
6 STATEWIDE REGIONAL TRAINING OFFICE
7
8 SECTION 1. (1) The Statewide Regional Training Office is established within the Depart-
9 ment of Public Safety Standards and Training.
10 (2) The office is under the supervision and control of the Statewide Regional Training
11 Officer, who is responsible for the performance of the duties, functions and powers of the
12 office.
13 (3) The Director of the Department of Public Safety Standards and Training shall appoint
14 the Statewide Regional Training Officer, who holds office at the pleasure of the director.
15
16 PROVISIONS RELATED TO THE STATE RESILIENCE OFFICER
17
18 SECTION 2. (1) The State Resilience Officer shall identify state agencies with responsi-
19 bility for one or more emergency support functions identified by the Federal Emergency
20 Management Agency.
NOTE: Matter in boldfaced type in an amended section is new; matter [italic and bracketed] is existing law to be omitted.
New sections are in boldfaced type.
LC 235

B-Eng. HB 4121
1 (2) Each state agency identified under subsection (1) of this section shall designate an
2 employee of the state agency as the Emergency Management Responsible Officer. The
3 Emergency Management Responsible Officer shall act as the primary liaison between the
4 state agency and state authorities related to emergency management, including the Oregon
5 Department of Emergency Management.
6 SECTION 3. ORS 401.913 is amended to read:
7 401.913. (1) The office of State Resilience Officer is created in the office of the Governor. The
8 office of State Resilience Officer shall direct, implement and coordinate hazard safety and resilience
9 goal setting and state agency planning and preparation to improve hazard safety and resilience, in-
10 cluding but not limited to planning and preparation for safety and resilience during and after
11 earthquake, tsunami, wildfire, flooding and other natural or manmade events.
12 (2) The State Resilience Officer shall lead statewide efforts to implement the Oregon Resilience
13 Plan, the Natural Hazard Mitigation Plan and other resilience plans adopted by the state.
14 (3) The State Resilience Officer shall facilitate policy standardization among state agen-
15 cies, prioritize investments for improving resilience posture and provide regular reports on
16 state agency resilience policy compliance, organizational preparedness, continuity of
17 governance procedures and measures of emergency readiness. Such reports may be made to
18 the Governor, appropriate committees of the Legislative Assembly or relevant public safety
19 advisory boards and commissions.
20 [(3)] (4) The State Resilience Officer shall lead executive branch agencies in continuity of op-
21 erations planning and continuity of government planning.
22 [(4)] (5) The Governor shall appoint an individual to serve as the State Resilience Officer, sub-
23 ject to confirmation by the Senate pursuant to Article III, section 4, of the Oregon Constitution.
24 [(5)] (6) The legislative branch of government and the judicial branch of government shall each
25 select an individual to monitor the effectiveness of hazard safety and resilience planning in their
26 branch.
27
28 OREGON DISASTER RECOVERY AUTHORITY
29
30 SECTION 4. (1) The Oregon Disaster Recovery Authority is established as an advisory
31 group within the Office of the Governor to direct emergency recovery in Oregon. The Gov-
32 ernor shall determine the membership of the authority, subject to subsection (2) of this
33 section.
34 (2) The Governor shall appoint at least eight individuals to serve as members of the au-
35 thority from among state agency leadership, local emergency managers and others with ex-
36 pertise in emergency management. The Governor shall seek the advice of the Oregon
37 Homeland Security Council when making appointments to the authority. Members of the
38 authority serve at the pleasure of the Governor.
39 (3) If the Governor declares a state of emergency under ORS 401.165, the Governor may
40 activate the authority. The authority remains activated until deactivated by order of the
41 Governor. The authority may remain activated notwithstanding the termination of a state
42 of emergency.
43 (4) When activated, the authority shall:
44 (a) Coordinate initial crisis services;
45 (b) Coordinate recovery and mitigation efforts throughout this state, using a framework
[2]

B-Eng. HB 4121
1 aligned with emergency support functions as defined by the Federal Emergency Management
2 Agency; and
3 (c) Coordinate the provision of emergency funding and other aid to local governments or
4 private entities.
5 (5) A majority of the members of the authority constitutes a quorum for the transaction
6 of business.
7 (6) Official action by the authority requires the approval of a majority of the members
8 of the authority.
9 (7) The Governor shall appoint one of the members of the authority to serve as chair-
10 person.
11 (8) The authority shall meet at times and places specified by the call of the Governor or
12 the chairperson. The authority may meet at times when the authority is not activated to
13 maintain readiness in the event of an emergency.
14 (9) The authority may adopt rules necessary for the operation of the authority.
15 (10) The Office of the Governor shall provide staff support to the authority.
16 (11) Members of the authority are not entitled to compensation or reimbursement for
17 expenses and serve as volunteers on the authority.
18 (12) All agencies of state government, as defined in ORS 174.111, are directed to assist
19 the authority in the performance of the duties of the authority and, to the extent permitted
20 by laws relating to confidentiality, to furnish information and advice the members of the
21 authority consider necessary to perform their duties.
22 SECTION 5. (1) If the Oregon Disaster Recovery Authority established under section 4
23 of this 2026 Act is activated pursuant to a declaration of emergency, the Governor may hire
24 additional state agency personnel under this section.
25 (2) Additional personnel hired under this section:
26 (a) May be placed at any state agency, including the Office of the Governor;
27 (b) Must perform duties related to the emergency, which may include taking over duties
28 previously performed by other state agency personnel who have been reassigned to
29 emergency-related tasks; and
30 (c) Must have their employment terminated no later than the date the authority is de-
31 activated under section 4 of this 2026 Act.
32 (3) Notwithstanding any other law relating to state government employment, additional
33 personnel hired under this section may be recruited and selected through any means the
34 Governor deems appropriate.
35 (4) The Governor’s hiring authority under this section is subject to the availability of
36 funding. The compensation of additional personnel hired under this section may be paid from
37 the Oregon Disaster Recovery Authority Fund established under section 6 of this 2026 Act.
38 SECTION 6. The Oregon Disaster Recovery Authority Fund is established in the State
39 Treasury, separate and distinct from the General Fund. The Oregon Disaster Recovery Au-
40 thority Fund consists of moneys appropriated, allocated, deposited or transferred to the fund
41 by the Legislative Assembly or otherwise. Moneys in the fund are continuously appropriated
42 to the Office of the Governor to pay for compensation for personnel hired under section 5
43 of this 2026 Act.
44
45 OREGON PREPAREDNESS GRANT ACCOUNT
[3]

B-Eng. HB 4121
1 SECTION 7. The Oregon Preparedness Grant Account is established in the State Treas-
2 ury, separate and distinct from the General Fund. The Oregon Preparedness Grant Account
3 consists of moneys appropriated, allocated, deposited or transferred to the fund by the Leg-
4 islative Assembly or otherwise. Moneys in the account are continuously appropriated to the
5 Oregon Department of Emergency Management for providing grants to local governments,
6 as defined in ORS 174.116, and tribal governments to support their compliance with ORS
7 401.305 (2).
