27 RESILIENCE HUBS AND NETWORKS
28
29 SECTION 9. ORS 409.760 is amended to read:
30 409.760. (1) As used in this section:
31 (a) “Resilience Hub” means a physical facility that is created, operated, managed or supported
32 by one or more local residents, local governments, tribal governments, public schools, community-
33 based organizations, faith-based organizations, nonprofit organizations, [or] nongovernmental organ-
34 izations or any other groups or entities located in Oregon, and that:
35 (A) Supports the needs of community members or tribal communities, facilitates gathering and
36 communication, distributes resources and otherwise enhances quality of life within a community;
37 (B) Serves as a central point for gathering, information sharing, and coordination in response
38 to a disruption in the community;
39 (C) Enhances the ability of a community to respond to and recover from a disruption in a com-
40 munity;
41 (D) Is positioned, operated and resourced on a day-to-day basis, during a disruption and during
42 recovery, to provide community resources, including but not limited to food, water, information
43 exchange, electronic charging stations, basic medical supplies and equipment proportionate to the
44 size of the community’s population and needs;
45 (E) Supports community cache sites and other support for community members who shelter in
[4]

B-Eng. HB 4121
1 place;
2 (F) Can provide child care, training, food distribution and other services that can help a com-
3 munity respond to unmet [social] needs to prepare for, respond to and recover from adverse events,
4 emergencies or disasters;
5 (G) Can provide, or can be retrofitted to provide, heating, cooling, air filtration and weather
6 protection; and
7 (H) Accommodates individuals with accessibility needs.
8 (b) “Resilience Network” means an association of facilities, organizations, resource providers
9 or service providers [outside of a physical Resilience Hub facility that collectively serve the purposes
10 of a Resilience Hub] that collectively supports community members to prepare for, adapt to
11 or respond to social, emotional and physical disruption generated by ongoing climate change
12 or other causes, and during and after an adverse event, emergency or disaster.
13 (2) The Department of Human Services shall, in consultation with the State Department of En-
14 ergy and the Oregon Health Authority, provide grants, [support and technical assistance for] equip-
15 ment, technical assistance, contracted services and any other type of support to individuals
16 or organizations located in Oregon for creating or sustaining Resilience Hubs and Resilience
17 Networks in Oregon. The Department of Human Services shall award:
18 (a) Grants for expenses related to planning and organizing Resilience Hubs and Resilience
19 Networks;
20 (b) Grants to support and expand development and operation of Resilience Hubs and Resilience
21 Networks to ensure that physical facilities can provide protection from extreme weather, can
22 maintain power and climate during power outages, have auxiliary communications capabilities and
23 are resilient following earthquakes, fires, tornadoes, floods, other extreme weather events and other
24 potential adverse events, emergencies or disasters[, emergencies or incidents]; and
25 (c) Grants for resources and services needed by communities to otherwise prepare for and re-
26 spond to adverse events, emergencies or disasters.
27 (3) Individuals or organizations located in Oregon and serving people in this state may apply
28 for grants by submitting an application that must include:
29 (a) A description of the purposes for which grant moneys will be expended, including a de-
30 scription of the services to be provided to the community by the Resilience Hub or Resilience
31 Network;
32 (b) A plan for implementing specific strategies to build resilience in a community;
33 (c) A description of additional resources available for purposes of the Resilience Hub or
34 Resilience Network;
35 (d) A description of the project’s ability to serve vulnerable populations and communities tradi-
36 tionally underrepresented in the public process, including communities of color, communities expe-
37 riencing lower incomes, tribal communities, rural communities, coastal communities, communities
38 with limited infrastructure, seniors, youth and persons with disabilities; and
39 (e) Any other information required by the department.
40 (4) The department shall execute grant agreements with grant recipients obligating recipients
41 to use grant moneys for purposes specified in the grant agreements. The department, in consultation
42 with the State Department of Energy and the Oregon Health Authority, shall determine the per-
43 missible purposes, applicant eligibility requirements, types of awards for a grant and eligible
44 equipment, technical assistance, services and support under this section based on the needs of
45 the Resilience Hub or Resilience Network. The department shall determine the needs of the
[5]

B-Eng. HB 4121
1 Resilience Hub or Resilience Network in consultation with the community, including populations
2 described in subsection (3)(d) of this section, within the locality in which the Resilience Hub or
3 Resilience Network operates.
4 (5) The Department of Human Services shall adopt rules necessary for the administration of this
5 section, including specifying the form and contents of an application for a grant under this section.
