7 OVERNIGHT TRAINING ACTIVITIES
8
9 SECTION 10. Notwithstanding any other provision of state or local law, a facility that is
10 used for emergency preparedness, response or recovery and that receives state funding is
11 authorized to host overnight training activities.
12
13 COUNTY AUTHORITY TO WAIVE CIVIL PENALTIES
14
15 SECTION 11. A county governing body may, by order or resolution, waive a civil penalty
16 imposed by the Oregon Health Authority or a local health authority under ORS 624.992 if the
17 civil penalty is imposed for a violation that occurred during a state of emergency declared
18 under ORS 401.165.
19
20 DEPARTMENT OF THE STATE FIRE MARSHAL
21
22 SECTION 12. The Department of the State Fire Marshal shall conduct a study of health
23 coverage disparities between paid and volunteer firefighters. The department shall submit a
24 report in the manner provided by ORS 192.245, and may include recommendations for legis-
25 lation, to the interim committees of the Legislative Assembly related to emergency man-
26 agement no later than September 15, 2027.
27 SECTION 13. Section 12 of this 2026 Act is repealed on January 2, 2028.
28
29 FINGERPRINTING BY ODEM
30
31 SECTION 14. The Oregon Department of Emergency Management shall require the fin-
32 gerprints of the following persons for the purpose of requesting a state or nationwide crim-
33 inal records check under ORS 181A.195:
34 (1) Persons employed or applying for employment by the department; and
35 (2) Persons who provide or seek to provide services to the department as a contractor
36 or subcontractor.
37
38 PUBLIC AND INDIVIDUAL ASSISTANCE PROGRAMS
39
40 SECTION 15. Sections 16 to 19 of this 2026 Act are added to and made a part of ORS
41 chapter 401.
42 SECTION 16. (1) The Oregon Department of Emergency Management shall establish and
43 administer a state infrastructure emergency recovery grant program, to be known as the
44 Oregon Public Assistance Grant Program, to issue grants to qualified recipients, subject to
45 available funding.
[6]

B-Eng. HB 4121
1 (2) Grants under the program must be used to pay for work performed before, during or
2 after an emergency to protect public health, safety or property, including, without limitation,
3 debris removal and work to protect or restore public services or public infrastructure.
4 (3) The Governor may activate the program if:
5 (a) The Governor determines that an emergency has occurred or is imminent and finds
6 that assistance from the state is warranted; and
7 (b) The department recommends that the program be activated.
8 (4) The Governor shall inactivate the program when the Governor finds that assistance
9 from the state is no longer warranted.
10 (5) While the program is active, the department may issue grants to qualified recipients
11 pursuant to requests from counties or tribal entities. A request on behalf of a city may be
12 made by the county in which a geographic majority of the city lies. Requests must be in
13 writing and must include the following information:
14 (a) Confirmation that the requester has taken appropriate action under the local emer-
15 gency plan;
16 (b) An estimate of the amount and severity of damages and losses and a description of
17 the impact of the emergency on the public and private sectors;
18 (c) A description of the nature and amount of local resources which have been or will
19 be committed to alleviate the results of the emergency;
20 (d) A preliminary estimate of the types and amount of supplementary state emergency
21 assistance needed; and
22 (e) A certification by the requester that the obligations and expenditures for the current
23 emergency will comply with all applicable cost sharing requirements agreed between the de-
24 partment and the requester.
25 (6) The department may adopt rules to administer and implement the provisions of this
26 section, including rules governing eligibility requirements, the form and manner of requests
27 and evaluation of requests by the department.
28 (7) As used in this section, “qualified recipient” means:
29 (a) A state agency;
30 (b) A local government;
31 (c) A federally recognized Indian tribe in Oregon;
32 (d) A school district or education service district; and
33 (e) A nonprofit organization that provides critical services or essential social services,
34 such as a hospital, long term care facility, school, community center, food assistance pro-
35 gram or shelter.
36 SECTION 17. The Oregon Public Assistance Grant Program Account is established in the
37 State Treasury, separate and distinct from the General Fund. Interest earned by the account
38 must be credited to the account. The account consists of moneys appropriated, allocated,
39 deposited or transferred to the account by the Legislative Assembly or otherwise and inter-
40 est earned on moneys in the account. The moneys in the account are continuously appro-
41 priated to the Oregon Department of Emergency Management to carry out the Oregon Public
42 Assistance Grant Program described in section 16 of this 2026 Act. The department shall
43 ensure that no more than 10 percent of the moneys in the account are used to pay costs of
44 coordination and distribution of assistance under the program.
45 SECTION 18. (1) The Department of Human Services shall establish and administer an
[7]

B-Eng. HB 4121
1 individual grant program, to be known as the Oregon Individual Assistance Grant Program,
2 to issue grants to address critical emergency-related needs of qualified individuals, subject
3 to available funding.
4 (2) The Governor may activate the program if:
5 (a) The Oregon Department of Emergency Management recommends that the program
6 be activated, the Governor determines that an emergency has occurred or is imminent and
7 the Governor finds that assistance from the state is warranted; or
8 (b) The Governor has declared an emergency under ORS 401.165.
9 (3) The Governor shall inactivate the program when the Governor finds that assistance
10 from the state is no longer warranted.
11 (4) While the program is active, the Department of Human Services may issue grants
12 pursuant to requests from counties or tribal entities. A request on behalf of a city may be
13 made by the county in which a geographic majority of the city lies. Requests must be in
14 writing and must include the following information:
15 (a) Confirmation that the requester has taken appropriate action under the local emer-
16 gency plan;
17 (b) An estimate of the amount and severity of damages and losses and a description of
18 the impact of the emergency on individuals and households;
19 (c) A description of the nature and amount of local resources which have been or will
20 be committed to alleviate the results of the emergency; and
21 (d) A preliminary estimate of the types and amount of supplementary state emergency
22 assistance needed.
23 (5) Grants under the program may be used only to pay for:
24 (a) The provision of services to qualified individuals for critical emergency-related needs,
25 which may include, without limitation:
26 (A) Temporary rental assistance;
27 (B) Hazard mitigation assistance;
28 (C) Repair or replacement of owner-occupied homes that serve as a primary residence,
29 including repair or replacement of privately owned access routes;
30 (D) Assistance with immediate needs;
31 (E) Essential personal property assistance;
32 (F) Assistance with other serious needs that are not covered by insurance; and
33 (G) Other critical emergency recovery services as approved by the Oregon Department
34 of Emergency Management; and
35 (b) Agreements with local governments, tribal entities or disaster recovery organizations
36 for the delivery of services described in paragraph (a) of this subsection, including payments
37 for staffing or other administrative needs.
38 (6) Assistance to individuals may be in the form of direct financial assistance or pay-
39 ments to another entity on behalf of individuals.
40 (7) The Department of Human Services, in consultation with the Oregon Department of
41 Emergency Management, may adopt rules to administer and implement the provisions of this
42 section.
43 (8) The Oregon Department of Emergency Management, in consultation with the De-
44 partment of Human Services, shall update the statewide emergency management plan pre-
45 pared under ORS 401.052 to incorporate the Oregon Individual Assistance Grant Program
[8]

B-Eng. HB 4121
1 into statewide disaster response and recovery planning. The plan must include, without lim-
2 itation, provisions for equitable distribution of assistance, coordination with local govern-
3 ments and community-based organizations, and integration with federal recovery programs
4 when applicable.
5 (9) As used in this section:
6 (a) “Hazard mitigation” means actions taken to reduce impacts of future emergencies.
7 (b) “Immediate need” means:
8 (A) A life-saving or life-sustaining item or activity that is essential to prevent, mitigate
9 or overcome an adverse condition caused by an emergency; and
10 (B) Other equipment that is essential for daily household needs.
11 (c) “Qualified individual” means:
12 (A) An individual who is displaced by an emergency from the individual’s primary resi-
13 dence;
14 (B) An individual whose primary residence is rendered uninhabitable by an emergency;
15 or
16 (C) An individual with a disability whose primary residence is rendered inaccessible or
17 uninhabitable to the individual as a result of damage caused by an emergency.
18 SECTION 19. The Oregon Individual Assistance Grant Program Account is established in
19 the State Treasury, separate and distinct from the General Fund. Interest earned by the
20 account must be credited to the account. The account consists of moneys appropriated, al-
21 located, deposited or transferred to the account by the Legislative Assembly or otherwise
22 and interest earned on moneys in the account. The moneys in the account are continuously
23 appropriated to the Oregon Department of Emergency Management. The department may
24 make moneys in the account available to the Department of Human Services to carry out
25 the Oregon Individual Assistance Grant Program described in section 18 of this 2026 Act.
